metadata.name: abstract with circles and squares #5
metadata.description: Imagine a universe of galaxies with infinite possibilities where colors dance in harmony with shapes, creating a unique landscape in every image. This collection of art made with JavaScript immerses you in a journey where code submits to the whim of chance. From hypnotic sinusoids to exuberant explosions of color, each piece is an expression, a window into the vastness of the creative potential residing at the heart of the programming language.

metadata.name: Chroma-Curves #75
metadata.description:
Each output is generated by layering Blender renders.

'Chroma-Curves' is inspired by mid-century modern minimalist art.

Each output consists of curves and circles on a colored background. The scale of the various components coupled with the carefully balanced colors create a bold, striking geometric design.

In live mode:
Click/tap the image to make a "Download image" button appear. Click this button to download a 1500x2000px PNG.

metadata.name: Shuǐmò Huà #26
metadata.description:
This collection is a mesmerizing blend of artificial intelligence and digital painting. Comprising 42 layers, it boasts the potential to generate 40,960 unique NFTs. However, only 32 NFTs will be minted in this collection, making each one a rare and exclusive piece.

Dive into a world of imagination and creativity, where algorithms and artistry converge to create stunning visuals.

Features:

42-layer composition
40,960 potential NFT variations
Limited edition of 32 NFTs
Experience the beauty of AI-generated art and own a piece of digital innovation.


Experience the elegance of traditional Chinese ink art in "Whimsical Crane," a captivating NFT masterpiece by َAI Rendered in black and red ink in the style of shuǐmò huà, this piece features a crane depicted with graceful strokes and delicate detailing. Despite its rough sketch quality, the crane exudes a sense of whimsy and charm, transporting viewers to a tranquil realm where nature reigns supreme. The combination of traditional Chinese aesthetics with the artist's unique interpretation results in a captivating fusion of cultures and artistic sensibilities. "Whimsical Crane" invites you to marvel at the beauty of simplicity and embrace the timeless allure of ink artistry.

metadata.name: Introspection #61
metadata.description:
Sketches of geometric shapes with scale symmetry.

"What does the mirror see when it looks in the mirror?"

--

- Live renderer best viewed in Chrome.
- Press "S" to export a standard resolution image.
- Press "P" to export an hi-res image.
- Press "G" to toggle the grain.

metadata.name: Specter of Fears #26
metadata.description:
In the dreamlike landscape of our minds, the specter of fears is like a wraith, ever-present and ethereal. It whispers in our ear, reminding us of all the things we dare not face. It is a shadow that falls across our hearts, casting a pall of doubt and uncertainty. But even as it haunts us, we must remember that it is a part of us. We must learn to accept its presence, and to use it to our advantage. For fear is not always a curse, it is a guide that shows us where we must grow stronger. It is a companion that walks with us through the dark night, illuminating the path ahead. By embracing our fears, we find the courage to face them, and to overcome them. We find the strength to live fully, to love fiercely, and to pursue our dreams with abandon.

Controls :

• Press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to make a capture and download a PNG with a resolution of x1, x2, x3 or x4.

———————

Specter of Fears by Ferdinand Dervieux, 2023
Made with Unity

metadata.name: Ataraxis #268
metadata.description:
Ataraxis (or a broken volume renderer) is an exploration in balancing discomfort and calm. The piece generates spaces on the fly that are designed to elicit strange and uncomfortable feelings - like a desolate, alien dreamscape - claustrophobic, surreal, not quite real yet strangely recognisable. But the idea is that while these spaces feel uncomfortable, they're also strangely, antilogically calming. The idea is to elicit a sanguine emotion, to make the viewer feel calm in a strange place, and to lead them somewhere else.

This work is the culmination of many years of work researching volumetric rendering techniques. This token uses a raymarching technique that is intentionally broken in various ways.

Controls:
Double-click to download
&w=X&h=y to change the size of the piece
&dpr=x to change the resolution of the pice - higher resolutions will result in slightly different artworks as the browser attempts to compensate for the overlarge canvas
&fullscreen=true to change the token to display the full size of your browser. This may impact the rendering of the token, so use with caution

metadata.name: 7VV1N5 #209
metadata.description:
GO BIG OR GO HOME.

After a week of minimalism code, our hero, the handsome artist Daniel, decided he needed something involving maximalism to reset the balance. Finding pairs to put together is satisfying.

Images will take 6-9 seconds to display and refresh between window resizing.

Use the z key or single click/tap to switch to "zoom" mode, which zooms in and fills the viewport; use z & tap/click to cycle through views. Use x and double-click/tap to go back to square mode.

Note: It doesn't work on Internet Explorer, because Microsoft. iOS is faster than Android.

-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-

z, click, tap - Switch to & cycle "zoom" mode
x, double-click, double-tap - Switch back out of "zoom" mode.
h - Toggle high-res (slow)
s - Download and save image (takes a few seconds, longer for high-res)

metadata.name: reborn #75
metadata.description:
This is an album of cities too ideal to ever materialise.

It consists of 256 algorithmically generated plans that resemble drawings of Vincenzo Scamozzi, Pietro Cataneo, Filarete and other theorists of the Italian Renaissance. The cities differ in size, the grid of the streets, the landscape around them and the people that inhabit their utopian walls. They carry names that are Italian exonyms of real European cities, drawing a vision of a different world that enacts a mixture of military perfection with social superiority. Flawless, harmonious, unconquerable and utterly impossible.

History brought us many theories about ideal cities, but very few examples exist today. Italian Palmanova or Polish Zamość are the few to remind us how hard it is to shape reality according to ideals. When confronted with the material world, its idealism becomes the city's grates foe.

To zoom, press a mouse button over the image or touch the screen. To pan, keep the mouse pressed and move it around.

metadata.name: The Face We Had #193
metadata.description:
The Face We Had is a series of generative, moving sculptures attempting to express the artists personal thoughts, experiences and inclinations related to meditative and altered states of consciousness. In a non-descriptive way, the piece aims to reflect the always changing nature of mind through patterns of movement and assemblages of form, color and organic shapes, endlessly revolving around a perceived point of origin.  

Although not intended as literal depictions, the elements interact in a way that could be interpreted as dance-like interactions between thought patterns, mental energy, feelings, fragments of memories and layers of personal identity. 



Interactive features:

space - pause/play
w - wireframe view
d - debug view (compute textures)
s - save screenshot

metadata.name: Concrete #156
metadata.description:
640 unique sketches of imaginary walls, inspired by the work of Norwegian architect Erling Viksjø (1910–1971) and his artist collaborators. Viksjø designed the Government Quarter in Oslo and invited artists from different disciplines to help design the facades and interiors of the buildings.

Viksjø’s aim was to “soften” modernist architecture. He invented «Natural Concrete», a type of concrete that deliberately exposes the mixed-in stones on its surface to give it warmth and a human touch. In my work, I have similar ambitions—using code instead of concrete.

The different styles of the piece are inspired by, and dedicated to some of the artists who worked together with Viksjø: Jakob Weidemann (~2%), Carl Nesjar (~18%), Odd Tandberg (~30%), and Tore Haaland (~50%).

In live mode, press ‘S’ to save an image at current resolution or ‘P’ to save a high-resolution file at 6000×6000px (this might take a while depending on your hardware).

Original artwork by Andreas Rau · Made with p5.js & glsl · Oslo, 2021

metadata.name: The Unrealized Painting #50
metadata.description:
Click to start.

The size of the canvas is proportional to the monitor. You can scale up using 1,2,3 and 4 of you keyboard to increase the quality of resolution (it may create some variations on the art itself, and it should be done before clicking on canvas)

The preview is only a sketch of the artwork, since the livecoding functions vary depending on the interaction.

This project was designed in Hydra.js for Desktop computers on Chrome.

Since it is a livecoding library there may be small differences in each code execution, but the deterministic character remains.

The machine waits for your command to start drawing - there is no plan or goal, sometimes the values assigned to the variables would lead to the construction of a visually recognizable work, but the fact that these values are randomized 4 times during the duration of the interaction breaks the logical line of visual conduction.

I can only appeal to Gestalt, and beg you to make the effort to see the whole divided between 4 apparently disconnected patterns. This is not just a code that generates noises, I am here making a testament to push once again the limit of abstraction, to perhaps convince you that there is immense beauty in discontinuity.

And it is worth commenting once again that without your click/command, the machine will be eternally lodged in the server waiting - and not knowing what it is waiting for. And this waiting is the most beautiful thing in the world, because the art is already determined to happen, its strokes and patterns were defined when the hash was tied to the code, the art was already made and already exists in the moment preceding this one - but for a computer time does not exist.

The Unrealized Painting has come to remind you that we, the ones with souls and who feel time, control the realizable and the unrealizable - and it will never stop being that way.
